IOM - Democratic Republic of the Congo
Through multiple grant activities, the program objective seeks to help extend the writ of the Government of Pakistan (GOP) and increase access to unbiased, public information about GOP policies.

The Middle East Response (MER) initiative is an innovative approach thatwill provide essential HIV, TB, and malaria services to eligible countrypopulations in Syria, Yemen and Syrian refugees in Jordan and Lebanon. This will be done through one regional grant management platform with the aim of improving responsiveness to the three diseases in the contextof emergencies in the aforementioned countries. The grant will consolidate current national grants in Syria, Yemen and the Emergency Fund Grant in Jordan and Lebanon. The scope of interventions under the grant was tailored to reflect the protracted conflict and refugee crisisin the abovementioned countries in consultation with technical partners.The grant will be managed by IOM through an integrated grant management platform, based in Amman, Jordan as IOM will capitalize on its country missions in the region to oversee grant implementation on the grounds, including in hard to reach areas of Yemen and Syria.

The overall objective of the proposed project is to contribute to improving police accountability and security for the population of Mbuji-Mayi through the reinforcement of community policing precepts.
This project will assist IOM in providing support to the Global Compact on Migration (GCM) process as mandated in the Modalities Resolution, andwill contribute to IOM's GCM funding appeal.

The project will address the urgent needs of water and sanitation service delivery in rural and peri-urban areas affected by recurrent drought and waterborne diseases such as acute watery diarrhea and cholera.
The overall goal of this project is to contribute to Indonesia's efforts to reduce vulnerability and enhance the resilience of communities to natural disasters.

As the protracted political and consequent humanitarian crises in Uganda's neighbouring countries of South Sudan and the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) continue, increased coordinated and effective humanitarian assistance is required to meet the basic needs of refugees already hosted by Uganda, as well as of those arriving on a daily basis. Through his project, IOM proposes sustainable and cost-effective WASH interventions at the two hosting settlements of Kyangwali and Kyaka II, as well as improved sanitation coverage at Palorinya.

As the economic and political crisis in Venezuela continues, Brazil has seen a significant influx of Venezuelan nationals crossing to the northern states of the country. In consultation with targeted populations, concerned national authorities and related partners, IOM will partner with civil society organizations to implement cash based assistance for food and temporary shelter to vulnerable Venezuelan nationals living outside of designated accommodation centres in Roraima state.

As a regional hub in the Pacific, Fiji is considered as an origin, transit and destination country in the context of international migration. Migration dynamics are becoming increasingly complex with growing impacts of both slow-onset and rapid-onset climate change. Efforts in addressing intersecting issues such as trafficking in persons(TIP) and a renewed focus on promoting sustainable labour mobility in the country through seasonal worker programmes with Australia and New Zealand highlight that well-managed migration is a priority for the Government of Fiji.

Building upon previous interventions and the lessons learned from Hurricanes Matthew, Irma and Maria, IOM aims to further strengthen the capacities of disaster response authorities at the regional and national level through: Non-Food Items (NFI) procurement and Warehousing Maintenance and Management, and enhance the knowledge of DPC staff in the handling of NFIs stockpile, through capacity building and training activities. Through the proposed interventions, IOM aims to continue supporting the process of knowledge and capacity transfer to permanent Haitian institutions who are best placed to address the problems faced by the Haitian state and population.
